Beam, F5 Networks, Humana, MEMC, Omnivision: U.S. Equity Movers

-- B y   K a i t l y n   K i e r n a n
-- 
2011-10-04T20:45:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-13/alico-angiodynamics-danaher-majesco-u-s-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in U.S. trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses
and prices are as of 4 p.m. in  New York .  Financial stocks rallied after a report in the Financial
Times that European officials were examining ways to coordinate
the recapitalization of Banks.  Morgan Stanley (MS)   advanced
12 percent, the most in the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index, to
$14.01.  JPMorgan Chase & Co. (JPM)   advanced 6.6 percent to
$30.26 for the biggest gain in the  Dow Jones Industrial Average .
 Bank of America Corp. (BAC)   rose 4.2 percent to $5.76.  Amedisys Inc. (AMED)   slumped 14 percent to $11.53, while
 Gentiva Health Services Inc. (GTIV)   slid 18 percent to $3.02.
The home-care providers were cut to “hold” from “buy” at
Deutsche Bank AG, which said the findings from a Finance
Committee report that the companies added visits to Medicare
patients to trigger federal bonuses could lead to further
investigations or even Medicare rate cuts.  AMR Corp. (AMR)   surged 21 percent, the most in the
Russell 1000 Index, to $2.39 after losing 33 percent yesterday.
The parent of  American Airlines  advanced after several analysts
said an American bankruptcy filing is unlikely. Rodman & Renshaw
upgraded the airline to “market outperform” from “market
perform.” Capstone Investments Inc. boosted the company to
“buy” from “hold.”  JetBlue Airways Corp. (JBLU)   rose 8 percent to $3.77.  Beam Inc. (BEAM US) jumped 6.8 percent to $44.75. The maker
of Jim Beam bourbon began trading on the New York Stock Exchange
after changing its name from Fortune Brands Inc., as the company
completed the spinoff of Fortune Brands Home & Security Inc.
(FBHS US).  F5 Networks Inc. (FFIV)   rose 10 percent, the most since
October 2010, to $77.63. The software maker had “significantly
improved performance” during the September quarter, William
Blair & Co. said in a note.  MEMC Electronic Materials Inc. (WFR)   gained 9.3 percent,
the most since Aug. 23, to $5.19. The maker of silicon wafers
was boosted to “buy” from “neutral” at Gilford Securities
Inc.  Nvidia Corp. (NVDA)   advanced 9.2 percent, the most since
Aug. 23, to $12.90. The maker of graphics chips was named by
Bank of America Corp. among  semiconductor companies  as “key
beneficiaries” of growing demand for smartphones.  Omnivision Technologies Inc. (OVTI)   gained 19 percent,
the most since Feb. 25, to $15.08. The primary supplier of
camera sensors for the iPhone 4S surged as  Apple Inc. (AAPL)  
Chief Executive Officer  Tim Cook  unveiled the new device.  Polycom Inc. (PLCM)   jumped 10 percent, the most since
April 25, to $19.52. The largest independent maker of
videoconference systems was boosted to “overweight” from
“equalweight” at Barclays Plc.  Transcept Pharmaceuticals Inc. (TSPT)   rose 34 percent to
$8.08, the highest price since July 12. The developer of
psychiatry and sleep medicine-related products said the U.S.
 Food and Drug Administration  will finish reviewing its
Intermezzo new drug application by Nov. 27.  Yahoo! Inc. (YHOO US) gained 6.9 percent, the most since
Aug. 29, to $14.46. The private-equity firm  Silver Lake , Alibaba
Group Holding Ltd. and  Russia ’s Digital Sky Technologies are
discussing a possible joint bid for the most-visited U.S. Web
portal, three people with direct knowledge of the matter said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kaitlyn Kiernan at 
 kkiernan2@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
